Patch Set 2:

This patch is more invasive, but provides a rather cool feature that propagates all the way into the logging files, as well as eliminates any ambiguity as to whether or not ReadReturn and the cache represent raw values or scaled values. Now, it's both! Instead of just holding double, it holds pair(double, double) so you get to remember both the original value and the final scaled value. Compatibility functions are provided, to keep the blast radius small.

This usage of pair is confusing because they're the same type.  So it's not clear upon usage which is scaled or not.  This is an excellent case for a structure.
OK, makes sense, a little structure like ReadReturn should do it.

Rebased to latest master. Removing leading underscores from "_scaled" and "_unscaled" member variables, to match what was done in 36695. Cleaned up usage of std::string_view versus std::string type.

Combined 51267 with this changeset, so we can abandon 51267 now: https://gerrit.openbmc-project.xyz/c/openbmc/phosphor-pid-control/+/51267
I have brought this up-to-date (just trivial cleanup of the list of mock methods). Any objection to merging it?
might be good to have the param comments here so that we know which value is scaled vs. unscaled with `/*value*/ value, /*unscaled*/ value` way
Done, added comment
I don't think we want to have function definition in an interface class right? since everything else here is pure virtual
OK, I made it "= 0" and it still worked! Happily, other people over time have changed the other subclasses, so this compatibility interface is no longer needed.
Revised as per comments
It turns out the ZoneMock class still used the compatibility interface, to my surprise. I added the missing mock declaration. Now it all works as it should.
This naming is weird though, we should consider using clang to change all of these variables automatically
Ah yeah, it was probably following the google standard long ago when venture@ was writing this.

Hmm. What should it be changed to? It would have a blast radius. The existing names make sense, in the greater context of the program, as they match the existing usages in the ValueCacheEntry and ReadReturn structures.
I meant this naming style doesn't follow OpenBMC C++ convention.
That is correct. It is old code that predates that. To avoid introducing needless churn, it was decided a while ago to let it be grandfathered in, if I remember correctly.
Going back to this now that it seems scaled = PWM and unscaled = RPM - should we just use those names instead?

No, that's a confusion of scaled/unscaled versus input/output. Scaled is normalized to the (0.0, 1.0) range, based on preconfigured min and max, but unscaled is whatever raw value comes from the inputs.

Ah! ok, could we add that in the comment here for future readers.

That was confusing to me
Now that, I can do. Added some nice comments.
Does string_view work here?
It might, but I don't want to introduce any bugs regarding string ownership, or introduce any new requirements upon the callers. A string reference works fine, and is not a copy.
Ack

Giving +2 to myself, after multiple +1 from others.

After a little over two years, it feels good to finally get this in!
